WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.000
So, my name is Mike Smith, I work at Pfizer in the UK, and I'm very pleased to be here

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.559
to talk to you today.

00:00:16.559 --> 00:00:19.240
Because I realise that people are lazy and easily distracted, I'm going to give you the

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:21.680
summary of the whole talk right up front.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:27.719
I use parameterised markdown reports with child documents to write up an exploratory

00:00:27.719 --> 00:00:32.200
analysis which I shared with some colleagues, some of whom were quantitative, some of whom

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:33.919
were not quantitative.

00:00:33.919 --> 00:00:38.360
The quantitative guys like the statistician on the team and clinical pharmacologists from

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:44.320
my department, including my manager, there were other non-quantitative guys, and it's

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:49.279
maybe unfair to call a clinician non-quantitative, but I'm going to.

00:00:49.279 --> 00:00:53.680
So this report was intended to serve all of those purposes.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:58.520
The analysis and the stuff I'm going to show today doesn't show that data, because of

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:03.040
confidentiality reasons, but it has very similar properties.

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:07.919
But what I really want to talk to you today is about cutlery drawers, and what they say

00:01:07.919 --> 00:01:08.919
about you.

00:01:08.919 --> 00:01:14.919
Now, these cutlery drawers are from people that you might bump into at this conference,

00:01:14.919 --> 00:01:21.239
and I think it's an interesting exercise in how people arrange things, structure things,

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:25.320
whether they do it by size, whether they do it by most frequently used, the differences

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:28.760
between perhaps US and European cutlery drawers.

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:31.919
But here's mine.

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:34.000
If you visit my house, you'll see my cutlery drawer.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.919
My wife will also be very surprised that you're visiting the house, and quite alarmed that

00:01:37.919 --> 00:01:39.959
you just want to see the cutlery drawer.

00:01:39.959 --> 00:01:45.559
Now, I did the Tidyverse Train the Trainer course, and thanks to Greg and Garrett for

00:01:45.559 --> 00:01:52.000
teaching on that, and I'm now taking every opportunity to have a learning experience

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:53.000
for the Tidyverse.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.260
So, if you take cutlery drawer, you might want to group by type.

00:01:56.260 --> 00:01:59.160
You want to gather those things together and arrange, and if you could do that from my

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:02.599
cutlery drawer, I would be really happy.

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:07.480
New hashtag for the conference is untidyverse.

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:13.919
And I'm really pleased that XKCD views the need for tidiness in the house in very similar

00:02:13.919 --> 00:02:14.919
ways.

00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:16.720
You can get Wi-Fi in a laptop.

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.479
You can put all your other possessions in a big bucket marked miscellaneous.

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:23.960
Okay, here's the premise for my talk.

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:28.720
My brain is lazy, shallow, and very easily distracted.

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:34.559
I hesitate to say that your brain is the same, but then we had Zhou Cheng up here telling

00:02:34.559 --> 00:02:36.720
us all that our intuition sucks.

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:40.199
So I think some people in this audience must have a brain that's lazy, shallow, and easily

00:02:40.199 --> 00:02:41.199
distracted.

00:02:42.199 --> 00:02:46.759
Now, we're all familiar with this plot that's from the R4 Data Science book, and it gives

00:02:46.759 --> 00:02:50.880
us a framework or a structure for understanding any analysis.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:54.399
And on the Not So Standard Deviations podcast recently, there was a good discussion about

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:59.199
this, and they came to the conclusion that really this is just a framework.

00:02:59.199 --> 00:03:00.600
It's a mental model.

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:05.759
Real data analysis don't necessarily have to follow all of these steps or in sequence.

00:03:05.759 --> 00:03:11.000
So let me explain to you something about my data analysis and how it works in practice.

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:14.880
And I'm sure that these experiences I'm going to relate are just for me alone.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:20.000
So it's not you guys, you have your stuff well together, this is just me.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.039
Okay, here we go.

00:03:22.039 --> 00:03:26.639
So I go and I get an email from my colleague who has a link to the data source.

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:31.880
I download that data source, I read it into R, I wrangle the data, and I plot it.

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:36.759
And then there's some time to step back, to reflect on my plot, to think about what it

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:41.880
looks like, so that after lunch I can come back and make better plots.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:45.800
And I might fit a preliminary model to the data, hey, it's the end of the day, it's time

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:46.800
to go home.

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:52.080
So the next day I come in and I find an email saying that the team has found an error in

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:55.240
the data, so here's the new version of the data.

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:59.559
And if your workflow is not reproducible, you're in a world of hurt here.

00:03:59.559 --> 00:04:05.559
So because I'm reproducible, I go to my markdown, I change the input data, I recompile my report,

00:04:05.559 --> 00:04:09.800
I see what differences there are, I check against the previous version, and we're good

00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:11.679
to go on.

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:16.799
I discuss the findings with my boss, I circulate the report, and my job is done.

00:04:16.799 --> 00:04:23.239
Oh, wait a minute, did anyone get kind of distracted by the text in light gray?

00:04:23.239 --> 00:04:25.640
Huh, so it's not just me then.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:31.000
Okay, the other thing is, did anyone notice that the transform and visualize bits from

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.040
the R for data science diagram were back to front and swapped over?

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:39.559
Cognitive load theory score one.

00:04:39.559 --> 00:04:41.640
So anyway, six months passed.

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:43.239
This is not an exaggeration.

00:04:43.239 --> 00:04:49.600
I got an email yesterday from my manager saying, you know that team and the work that you did

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:50.600
for them?

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:53.519
They're interested in your results, can you dig them out and share them?

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:59.720
Now if you're anything like me, what happens is you pop open your R script or something

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:05.760
like that, and you think, what the heck did I do, right?

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:10.720
To the rescue, for me, comes R Markdown and notebooks, right?

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:12.239
These guys are now saving my life.

00:05:12.239 --> 00:05:13.880
I love notebooks.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:17.839
Thank you, eBay and team who are working on notebooks.

00:05:17.839 --> 00:05:21.000
And whenever you're writing, you need to think about who is the audience that you're writing

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.000
for.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.160
Well, for me, when I write a notebook, it's for distracted me.

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:31.799
It's the one that is hopping between activities, not focusing 24-7 on my nice little analysis,

00:05:31.799 --> 00:05:34.200
but with a billion things to do.

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:38.200
It's also the future me, the six months later me that pops open the Markdown document and

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:44.000
goes, all right, I'm good, because I've got my code, I've got the explanation, I can see

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.079
the outputs.

00:05:45.079 --> 00:05:48.559
I've even got text that explains what I was thinking.

00:05:48.559 --> 00:05:49.559
Hurrah.

00:05:49.559 --> 00:05:50.559
Right?

00:05:50.559 --> 00:05:54.040
But here's another audience for your reports.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:58.640
It could be a quantitative colleague who wants to see code, who wants to see data,

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:03.920
who wants to see your assumptions, who wants to dig into your residual plots from your

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:04.920
model.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:09.359
I can guarantee you the non-quantitative people won't want to see that.

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:13.279
So it's good if you can try to balance up and try to have techniques that would allow

00:06:13.279 --> 00:06:18.679
you to hide the bits that the non-quantitative people want to see, but also allow the quantitative

00:06:18.679 --> 00:06:23.559
people to get what they want from that report.

00:06:24.079 --> 00:06:26.799
So, back to notebooks just for a second.

00:06:26.799 --> 00:06:31.480
I realize, and again, thank you E-Wait, that there is a debate here.

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:37.000
But for analysis, if you're writing analysis, I think notebooks are fantastic.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:45.399
And back to Garrett's stuff about Markdown, if you're writing more comments than code,

00:06:45.399 --> 00:06:47.839
then you should be using R Markdown in notebooks.

00:06:47.839 --> 00:06:53.000
If you're writing more code than comments, write more comments and use R Markdown.

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:58.519
But, if you're not writing for analysis, then I really recommend you go and read this blog

00:06:58.519 --> 00:07:01.279
post because it's very interesting.

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:07.040
Also, because I'm lazy, I knew my manager would come back and ask for the same analysis

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:10.600
across the three endpoints that are in my data.

00:07:10.600 --> 00:07:15.920
So I'm trying to set up my report to answer quantitative, non-quantitative, and for three

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:18.200
different endpoints.

00:07:18.239 --> 00:07:25.000
So, if you have to paste your code more than three times, what should you do?

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.160
Write a function.

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:31.559
If you have to perform an analysis across more than three endpoints, what do you do?

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:35.079
Do you write multiple R Markdown reports?

00:07:35.079 --> 00:07:37.079
Parameterized reports.

00:07:37.079 --> 00:07:38.079
Thanks very much.

00:07:38.079 --> 00:07:39.079
Otherwise, why would you be here?

00:07:39.079 --> 00:07:41.079
I mean, honestly, I'm not that entertaining.

00:07:41.079 --> 00:07:45.079
Anyway, back to XKCD.

00:07:45.119 --> 00:07:47.920
XKCD talks about automation.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:50.200
And the top panel talks about the theory of automation.

00:07:50.200 --> 00:07:52.239
It's a bit like the theory of data science.

00:07:52.239 --> 00:07:55.359
It's the mental model for what we all hope will happen.

00:07:55.359 --> 00:07:56.640
We automate things.

00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:59.079
We can get on and we can do completely different work.

00:07:59.079 --> 00:08:03.519
The reality is that when you automate things and try to be clever, often you wind up troubleshooting

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:06.640
the thing that's gone wrong.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:11.000
But here's the thing that makes all of this work, is the YAML header parameters.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.799
If you're familiar with R Markdown, then you'll know about the YAML header.

00:08:15.799 --> 00:08:20.320
If you're not familiar with R Markdown, this may be a bit of a stretch.

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:21.320
But bear with me.

00:08:21.320 --> 00:08:22.320
Okay.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:24.959
So the YAML header says something about the document.

00:08:24.959 --> 00:08:28.000
It says the title, the author, the date it was done.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.640
And it says something about the formatting for the output.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:34.760
So here it's an HTML document and it has certain attributes.

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:38.479
The bit I've highlighted in red is the bit we need to focus on.

00:08:38.479 --> 00:08:42.479
These are parameters that you can pass into your document.

00:08:42.479 --> 00:08:47.880
And it comes into your document, you know, like an R object that you can then use.

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:48.960
You can compute on.

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:51.239
You can do all kinds of clever things with it.

00:08:51.239 --> 00:08:58.119
So here in my document, in my header, I've got a parameter which is called endpoint.

00:08:58.119 --> 00:09:01.840
It has a default value of HamDTL17.

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:04.679
But it also has three distinct choices.

00:09:04.679 --> 00:09:06.679
So it's not just a free text.

00:09:06.679 --> 00:09:09.840
You have to choose one of those three options.

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:12.960
Also I've got a Boolean parameter which is called quantitative audience.

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:16.280
And if that is true, then I'm going to include a bunch of other stuff.

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:20.559
But if it's false, then this is a stripped back report just for the non-quantitative

00:09:20.559 --> 00:09:21.559
audience.

00:09:21.559 --> 00:09:22.559
Okay?

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:28.559
Now, the specification of those is very close to what you might do with shiny inputs if

00:09:28.559 --> 00:09:31.080
you're familiar with them.

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:34.799
So then when you're ready, you can choose to knit that document.

00:09:34.799 --> 00:09:37.760
And if you just hit the knit button, you'll get the default values.

00:09:37.760 --> 00:09:43.119
But if you can choose to knit with parameters, then a little pop-up box comes up, a bit like

00:09:43.119 --> 00:09:44.119
shiny.

00:09:44.119 --> 00:09:45.119
You choose your endpoints.

00:09:45.119 --> 00:09:47.640
You determine whether you're in the quantitative audience.

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:49.280
And you can knit your document.

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:53.440
Now, parameters are really cool because you can do things with them.

00:09:53.440 --> 00:10:01.119
So here I've embedded the parameter endpoint, or it's param$endpoint, and that value can

00:10:01.119 --> 00:10:03.080
get pasted into text.

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:07.080
So then you can talk about the endpoint for the report that you're talking about.

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:12.200
You can pass the parameter in and use it within the markdown text.

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:17.219
You can use it in the header or the access labels for the ggplot.

00:10:17.219 --> 00:10:23.059
And so it can be used in a variety of ways, sky's the limit, okay?

00:10:23.059 --> 00:10:28.520
But the other thing that's kind of cool is that you can use the parameters in determination

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:31.159
of whether the code chunk runs or not.

00:10:31.239 --> 00:10:37.520
So here I'm saying if it's not the quantitative audience, in other words, if it's the non-quantitative

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:42.719
audience, then hide all the code, right?

00:10:42.719 --> 00:10:45.960
The other thing that makes this work is in the top box, and that's because what I did

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:51.239
was to rename all of the endpoint columns in my data with the name of the parameter

00:10:51.239 --> 00:10:56.840
endpoint so that then downstream I can fit a linear model on something called outcome

00:10:56.840 --> 00:11:00.080
and not on something called param$endpoint, okay?

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:05.440
It just cleans up the code and it makes things easier to see further down.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:12.359
You can choose to run code chunks at all based on parameters.

00:11:12.359 --> 00:11:17.479
The other thing that I've used is a child document, because if you remember when I was

00:11:17.479 --> 00:11:22.159
presenting this to the quantitative audience, I want to pull in some extra information.

00:11:22.159 --> 00:11:27.280
The code chunks will run or not according to the settings here, but you might want some

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:31.080
additional bit of text that comes in and says, okay, for the quantitative guys, here's

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:35.359
what I'm doing, and that's where the child document comes in.

00:11:35.359 --> 00:11:41.559
They're just plain text, R Markdown files, and those guys get pulled in if needed.

00:11:41.559 --> 00:11:46.159
So for the quantitative audience, what you see here is that we're showing the code, I've

00:11:46.159 --> 00:11:50.940
run the chunk, you can see the data, and the bit at the bottom that says data manipulations

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:54.280
is that child document text.

00:11:55.280 --> 00:12:01.799
Now, Tarif kind of stole some of my thunder in his opening talk, but that's okay, he's

00:12:01.799 --> 00:12:04.679
the president, that's fine.

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:08.280
What you can do in RStudio Connect is that you can go across to the left-hand side where

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:14.760
it says input, you can pop that open, and it will have the same ability to select parameters

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:18.960
and define what the report is going to run.

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:23.919
But the other nice thing is that if you do that and you save those things as named objects,

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:30.200
then in RStudio Connect you've just got this little drop-down menu of pre-compiled reports.

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:35.719
So what you might want to do is to set up, you know, commonly used, here it was all right

00:12:35.719 --> 00:12:41.799
because there's only six reports in total that could be done, but it's that ability

00:12:41.799 --> 00:12:45.919
that if someone has already run this report, you can just quickly grab it and it doesn't

00:12:45.919 --> 00:12:48.400
have to recompile.

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:52.640
Okay, so more about parameterization.

00:12:52.640 --> 00:12:59.000
So what we saw was when we rendered the report, you go to the render with parameters or knit

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.960
with parameters, but from the command line you can pass in your parameters just through

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:08.919
a list like this, okay, and it's really straightforward.

00:13:08.919 --> 00:13:12.799
The second thing is you might want to change your analysis depending on which endpoint

00:13:12.799 --> 00:13:13.799
you're looking at.

00:13:13.799 --> 00:13:18.359
If you're looking at a categorical outcome, you're not going to want to fit a linear model,

00:13:18.359 --> 00:13:21.260
or at least you shouldn't.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:26.780
So in that case you may want to tailor your analysis depending on the parameter endpoint,

00:13:26.780 --> 00:13:31.940
but again it's just, you know, another thing that you can compute on within a chunk.

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:36.780
Also if something goes wrong with your analysis, then if you're handling the error appropriately,

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:41.140
if you're using try-catch or something like that, you can compute on that and then have

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:45.700
a trial document that says something helpful like, you know, something's gone wrong, contact

00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:51.419
your friendly data scientist, you know, here's his details, okay?

00:13:51.419 --> 00:13:57.780
So the other last thing back to XKCD is how long should you spend parameterizing your

00:13:57.780 --> 00:14:00.260
report and setting things up?

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:02.539
Now this is kind of alarming.

00:14:02.539 --> 00:14:09.419
I know that JD Long has also talked to this graph today, but the thing I want to impress

00:14:09.419 --> 00:14:13.780
on you is basically, you know, this is over five years.

00:14:13.859 --> 00:14:19.299
So, you know, if you spend a day or two days or five days sorting this out, then, and only

00:14:19.299 --> 00:14:23.780
two people are going to use it once every six months, maybe I wasted my time.

00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:27.340
But on the other hand I got a conference talk out of it, so that's good.

